[[File:Thoughts on Government.jpg|thumb|The book ''Thoughts on Government'' by John Adams (1776)]]
'''''Thoughts on Government''''', or in full '''''Thoughts on Government, Applicable to the Present State of the American Colonies''''', was written by [[John Adams]] during the spring of 1776 in response to a resolution of the [[North Carolina Provincial Congress]] which requested Adams' suggestions on the establishment of a new [[government]] and the drafting of a [[constitution]]. Adams says that "Politics is the Science of human Happiness -and the Felicity of Societies depends on the Constitutions of Government under which they live." Many of the ideas put forth in Adams' [[essay]] were adopted in December 1776 by the framers of [[North Carolina Constitution#Constitution of 1776|North Carolina's first constitution]].

The document is notable in that Adams sketches out the three branches of American government: the [[Federal government of the United States#Executive branch|executive]], [[Federal government of the United States#Judicial branch|judicial]], and [[Federal government of the United States#The legislative branch|legislative branches]], all with a system of [[Separation of powers|checks and balances]].  Furthermore, in response to [[Common Sense (pamphlet)|''Common Sense'']] by [[Thomas Paine]], Adams rejects the idea of [[unicameralism|a single legislative body]], fearing it may become tyrannical or self-serving (as in the case of the [[Dutch Republic|Netherlands]] at the time).  Thus, Adams also conceived of the idea that two legislative bodies should serve as checks to the power of the other.<ref>''[[John Adams (book)|John Adams]]'' by [[David McCullough]], Simon and Schuster Paperbacks, New York, 2001.  Pg 102-103. {{ISBN|978-0-684-81363-9}}</ref>

